    id: 'lesson-17', title: 'C-Strings & String Functions', category: 'arrays', order_index: 17,
    content: '## C-Strings (Null-Terminated Strings)\n\nC-strings are arrays of characters ending with null character `\\0`.\n\n```cpp\nchar greeting[] = "Hello";  // Stores: \'H\',\'e\',\'l\',\'l\',\'o\',\'\\0\'\n```\n\n## Common Functions (<cstring>)\n| Function | Description |\n|----------|-------------|\n| `strlen(s)` | Length excluding null |\n| `strcpy(dst, src)` | Copy (dangerous — no bounds check!) |\n| `strncpy(dst, src, n)` | Copy at most n chars |\n| `strcat(dst, src)` | Append src to dst |\n| `strcmp(s1, s2)` | Compare (0 if equal) |\n| `strstr(s, sub)` | Find substring |\n| `strtok(s, delim)` | Tokenize (destructive!) |\n\n```cpp\nchar str1[50] = "Hello";\nchar str2[] = " World";\nstrcat(str1, str2);         // "Hello World"\ncout << strlen(str1);       // 11\n```\n\n## Buffer Overflow Danger\n```cpp\nchar buffer[5];\nstrcpy(buffer, "This is way too long!");  // OVERFLOW! UB!\n\n// Safer:\nstrncpy(buffer, "This is way too long!", sizeof(buffer) - 1);\nbuffer[sizeof(buffer) - 1] = \'\\0\';\n```\n\n## String to Number Conversion\n```cpp\n#include <cstdlib>\nint i = atoi("42");\ndouble d = atof("3.14");\nlong val = strtol("42abc", &end, 10);  // val=42, with error checking\n```\n\n## Why Prefer std::string\n- Error-prone (overflows, null termination)\n- Inconvenient (no + operator)\n- Unsafe (no bounds checking)\n\nModern C++ strongly recommends `std::string` over C-strings.',
    code_example: '#include <iostream>\n#include <cstring>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n    char name[50] = "John";\n    char lastName[] = " Doe";\n    strcat(name, lastName);\n    cout << "Full: " << name << endl;\n    cout << "Length: " << strlen(name) << endl;\n\n    char input[50];\n    cout << "Enter something: ";\n    cin >> input;\n    if (strcmp(input, "quit") == 0) cout << "Exiting" << endl;\n    else cout << "You entered: " << input << endl;\n\n    return 0;\n}'
